        treatment: "Beta-thalassemia major: chronic transfusion (PRBCs q3-4 weeks to keep Hb >9-10), iron chelation (deferasirox 20-40mg/kg/day or deferoxamine 20-40mg/kg/day SC over 8-12h, 5-7 days/week, or deferiprone 75-100mg/kg/day TID) to prevent iron overload. Splenectomy if hypersplenism causing increased transfusion requirement (after age 5-6). Folic acid 1mg daily. Hematopoietic stem cell transplantation (curative, best if <14 years). Gene therapy (experimental). Thalassemia intermedia: transfusions only during crises, splenectomy if needed, avoid iron overload. Thalassemia trait: no treatment, genetic counseling.",
        complication: ["Iron overload (from transfusions, causes cardiomyopathy, liver cirrhosis, diabetes, hypothyroidism, hypogonadism, requires chelation)", "Cardiomyopathy (leading cause of death in thalassemia major, from iron overload, presents with heart failure, arrhythmias)", "Liver cirrhosis (from iron overload, 10-20%)", "Endocrine dysfunction (diabetes 10%, hypothyroidism 5-10%, hypogonadism 20-30%)", "Growth failure (from anemia and iron overload)", "Delayed puberty (from iron overload affecting pituitary)", "Osteoporosis (from bone marrow expansion and chelation)", "Splenic sequestration (sudden splenic enlargement, severe anemia, shock)", "Infections (post-splenectomy: encapsulated organisms, require penicillin and vaccines)", "Death (without transfusion, <5 years; with transfusion, 30-40 years from iron overload)"],
        prevention: "Prenatal screening (carrier testing for at-risk populations), genetic counseling, prenatal diagnosis (chorionic villus sampling at 10-12 weeks), folic acid supplementation during pregnancy (does not prevent thalassemia, but prevents NTDs)",
        epidemiology: "Beta-thalassemia: 1 in 100,000 in US, 1 in 10,000 in Europe, 1 in 100 in Mediterranean, Middle East, India, Southeast Asia. Alpha-thalassemia: most common in Southeast Asia (1 in 20), Africa, Mediterranean. 60,000 births annually worldwide."
