        symptoms: ["Asymptomatic (most)", "Mild headache", "Edema (dependent, not diagnostic)", "No visual disturbances, no epigastric pain, no nausea/vomiting (differentiates from pre-eclampsia)"],
        signs: ["BP ≥140/90 on two occasions, 4h apart, after 20 weeks gestation", "No proteinuria (dipstick negative, or <300mg/24h)", "Normal LFTs, platelets, creatinine", "No symptoms or signs of severe pre-eclampsia", "No fetal growth restriction or oligohydramnios"],
        ddx: ["Chronic hypertension (BP ≥140/90 before 20 weeks or before pregnancy)", "White coat hypertension (elevated BP in clinic, normal at home, no proteinuria, normal labs)", "Pre-eclampsia (proteinuria or end-organ dysfunction develops in 25-50% of gestational hypertension)", "Transient hypertension of pregnancy (resolves postpartum, no progression to pre-eclampsia)"],
        ix: ["BP monitoring (clinic and home)", "Urine protein (dipstick at each prenatal visit, if 1+ then protein/creatinine ratio or 24h urine)", "CBC, platelets", "LFTs, creatinine", "Fetal monitoring (ultrasound for growth and fluid, NST/BPP twice weekly after 32 weeks)"],
        treatment: "Expectant management (close monitoring). Antihypertensives: not routinely indicated unless BP ≥160/105 (or ≥150/100 with risk factors). If treatment needed: labetalol 100-400mg PO BID-TID, nifedipine XL 30-60mg PO daily, or methyldopa 250-500mg PO BID-QID. Deliver at 37-40 weeks (induction at 37-38 weeks recommended to reduce progression to pre-eclampsia). Monitor BP twice weekly, urine protein weekly, labs weekly. Educate patient on symptoms of severe pre-eclampsia (headache, visual changes, epigastric pain, dyspnea, decreased fetal movement).",
        complication: ["Progression to pre-eclampsia (25-50%, higher if early onset (<32 weeks), or BP >150/100)", "Progression to severe pre-eclampsia (10-20%)", "Fetal growth restriction (5-10%)", "Placental abruption (1-2%)", "Preterm delivery (10-20%)", "Postpartum hypertension (50% persist >6 weeks, 10% develop chronic hypertension)"],
        prevention: "Low-dose aspirin 81mg daily starting at 12-28 weeks for high-risk women (prior pre-eclampsia, chronic hypertension, diabetes, obesity, multiple gestation, autoimmune disease, renal disease). Calcium supplementation (1.5-2g daily) for low-calcium intake populations. Regular prenatal care, BP monitoring, lifestyle modification (weight loss, exercise, low sodium diet if overweight).",
        epidemiology: "5-10% of pregnancies, most common in nulliparas (70%), more common in obese, multiple gestation, advanced maternal age (>35), African American. 50% resolve within 6 weeks postpartum, 50% develop chronic hypertension within 5-10 years."
