        signs: ["Pallor (conjunctiva, palms, nail beds)", "Tachycardia", "Systolic flow murmur", "Koilonychia (spoon nails, chronic iron deficiency)", "Angular cheilitis", "Glossitis (smooth, red tongue)"],
        ddx: ["Iron deficiency anemia (80-90% of anemia in pregnancy, microcytic, low ferritin)", "Thalassemia trait (microcytic, normal ferritin, elevated HbA2, family history)", "Anemia of chronic disease (normocytic or microcytic, normal or elevated ferritin)", "Megaloblastic anemia (B12 or folate deficiency, macrocytic, hypersegmented neutrophils)", "Hemolytic anemia (sickle cell, hereditary spherocytosis, autoimmune, elevated LDH, low haptoglobin)"],
        ix: ["CBC (Hb, MCV, MCH, RDW)", "Iron studies (ferritin <30mcg/L indicates iron deficiency, <12 severe)", "Peripheral smear (microcytes, hypochromic cells, target cells, schistocytes, blasts)", "B12, folate (if macrocytic)", "Hemoglobin electrophoresis (if suspected sickle cell or thalassemia)", "Stool occult blood (if suspected GI bleed)"],
        treatment: "Iron deficiency: ferrous sulfate 325mg (65mg elemental iron) PO TID (or 325mg BID if mild) + vitamin C (orange juice) to enhance absorption. Take between meals, avoid with milk, tea, coffee. If intolerant or severe anemia (Hb <8): IV iron (ferric carboxymaltose 1000mg IV, or iron sucrose 200mg IV q3-7 days x5 doses). Folate deficiency: folic acid 1mg PO daily. B12 deficiency: cyanocobalamin 1000mcg IM monthly. Transfuse PRBCs if Hb <6 (or <7 with symptoms, or <8 with cardiovascular disease, or active bleeding). Treat underlying cause (parasites, bleeding).",
        complication: ["Maternal: increased risk of postpartum hemorrhage (2-3x), blood transfusion, prolonged hospital stay, postpartum depression, fatigue affecting quality of life", "Fetal: intrauterine growth restriction (2-3x), preterm birth (2x), low birth weight, neonatal anemia, cognitive impairment (long-term)"],
        prevention: "Iron supplementation: 30-60mg elemental iron daily for all pregnant women (routine) starting at first prenatal visit. Folate: 400-800mcg daily (prevents NTDs). Dietary sources: red meat, poultry, fish, leafy greens, legumes, fortified cereals. Screen for anemia at first prenatal visit and again at 24-28 weeks.",
        epidemiology: "Most common medical disorder in pregnancy, 30-50% of pregnant women globally, 15-20% in developed countries, 80-90% due to iron deficiency, highest in third trimester, adolescents, multiple gestation, short interpregnancy interval (<6 months), low socioeconomic status, vegetarian"
