        ddx: ["Placental abruption (painful, tender uterus, concealed or revealed bleeding, retroplacental clot on ultrasound)", "Vasa previa (fetal vessels over os, bleeding after membrane rupture, fetal bradycardia, Doppler ultrasound)", "Cervical lesions (cervicitis, polyp, ectropion, cancer, bleeding after intercourse, speculum exam shows lesion)", "Marginal sinus rupture (marginal placenta, bleeding, no pain, ultrasound shows no previa)"],
        ix: ["Transabdominal ultrasound (placenta location, degree of previa (complete, partial, marginal), cervical length, placental edge to internal os distance, rule out accreta (loss of hypoechoic retroplacental zone, bridging vessels, lacunae))", "Transvaginal ultrasound (safely measures distance from placental edge to internal os, more accurate than transabdominal, <1cm from os or overlapping indicates previa, does NOT provoke bleeding)", "MRI (if suspected placenta accreta, increta, percreta, or posterior placenta)", "CBC, blood type and crossmatch (for potential transfusion)", "Fetal monitoring (NST, BPP)"],
        treatment: "Antepartum: hospitalization for first bleeding episode (if <36 weeks, bleeding stops, maternal and fetal stability). Expectant management: bed rest (modified), pelvic rest (no intercourse, no vaginal exams), serial ultrasound q2-4 weeks to monitor placental migration (50% resolve by term), corticosteroids (betamethasone 12mg IM q24h x2) if <34 weeks, tocolytics if preterm labor (nifedipine 20mg PO q6h), RhIg if Rh-negative. Delivery: planned C-section at 36-37 weeks (if asymptomatic, no bleeding, placenta covering os). Emergency C-section for: massive bleeding, hemorrhagic shock, fetal distress, or labor. Intraoperative: have blood products available, consider uterine artery embolization, or hysterectomy if accreta.",
