        ix: ["Serum acetaminophen level (draw at 4h post-ingestion, plot on Rumack-Matthew nomogram to predict toxicity, level >150mcg/mL at 4h, >50 at 12h, >10 at 24h indicates hepatotoxicity risk)", "LFTs (AST/ALT (elevated, >1000 indicates hepatotoxicity, >10,000 in severe), ALP, GGT, bilirubin (elevated))", "Coagulation profile (PT/INR >1.5 indicates hepatotoxicity, >2.5 severe, >4.0 poor prognosis)", "CBC, electrolytes, BUN, creatinine (AKI)", "Ammonia (elevated, >100 indicates severe, >200 poor prognosis)", "Glucose (hypoglycemia, poor prognosis)", "Blood gas (metabolic acidosis, pH <7.3 poor prognosis)", "King's College Criteria for liver transplantation: pH <7.3, or INR >6.5 and Cr >3.4, or lactate >3.5 after resuscitation, or grade III-IV encephalopathy"],
