        symptoms: ["Altered mental status (confusion, agitation, delirium, coma)", "Seizures (generalized tonic-clonic)", "Dry mouth (anticholinergic)", "Blurred vision (anticholinergic)", "Urinary retention (anticholinergic)", "Constipation (anticholinergic)", "Palpitations", "Syncope", "Cardiac arrest"],
        signs: ["Tachycardia (>100/min, anticholinergic)", "Hypotension (SBP <90, from alpha-blockade, myocardial depression)", "Wide QRS (>100ms, sodium channel blockade, >160ms predicts seizures and arrhythmias)", "Prolonged QT (>440ms)", "Right axis deviation (terminal R wave >3mm in aVR, most specific for TCA toxicity)", "Seizures", "Altered mental status", "Mydriasis (dilated pupils, anticholinergic)", "Dry mucous membranes (anticholinergic)", "Hypothermia", "Ileus (hypoactive bowel sounds)"],
        ddx: ["Other sodium channel blockers (quinidine, procainamide, flecainide, propafenone, cocaine, diphenhydramine, carbamazepine) - similar ECG findings, history of ingestion", "Anticholinergic overdose (atropine, antihistamines, antipsychotics, plants (jimson weed)) - similar mental status, mydriasis, tachycardia, but no wide QRS", "Opioid overdose (miosis, respiratory depression, no wide QRS)", "Hypoglycemia (glucose <50, no wide QRS, no mydriasis)", "Intracranial hemorrhage (focal deficits, hypertension, no wide QRS)"],
        ix: ["ECG (most important: QRS width >100ms (toxicity), >160ms (severe, risk of seizures, arrhythmias), terminal R wave >3mm in aVR (sensitivity 80%, specificity 90%), QT prolongation, right axis deviation", "CBC, electrolytes (K, Mg, Ca), BUN, creatinine", "ABG (metabolic acidosis)", "Troponin (if cardiac ischemia)", "TCA level (quantitative, not available stat, confirmatory)", "Toxicology screen (urine, blood, for TCAs, other drugs)", "Chest X-ray (pulmonary edema)"],
        treatment: "ABCs: intubation if coma, seizures, or respiratory failure. Sodium bicarbonate 1-2 mEq/kg IV bolus (for QRS >100ms, arrhythmias, hypotension). Repeat until QRS <100ms (target serum pH 7.45-7.55). Then sodium bicarbonate infusion (150mEq in D5W at 2-3mL/kg/h). Avoid hyperventilation (alkalosis beneficial, but hyperventilation causes cerebral vasoconstriction). Magnesium sulfate 2g IV (for Torsade de pointes, if QT prolonged). Lidocaine 1-1.5mg/kg IV (for VT, if refractory to bicarbonate, avoid class Ia (procainamide) and class III (amiodarone) antiarrhythmics (worsen sodium channel blockade)). IV fluids (NS or LR 1-2L bolus) for hypotension. Vasopressors: norepinephrine (preferred, avoid dopamine (may worsen arrhythmias)). Seizures: benzodiazepines (lorazepam 2-4mg IV, or diazepam 5-10mg IV), avoid phenytoin (sodium channel blocker, worsens toxicity). Activated charcoal 50g PO/NG (if within 2-4h of ingestion). Lipid emulsion 1.5mL/kg IV (20% lipid emulsion), then 0.25mL/kg/min x30-60min (if refractory to bicarbonate, for cardiotoxicity). Hemodialysis (ineffective, TCAs protein-bound). ICU care.",
