        ix: ["Blood lead level (BLL, normal <5 mcg/dL, mild 5-44, moderate 45-69, severe >70, acute poisoning >100)", "CBC (microcytic anemia (basophilic stippling on smear), normal MCV early, then microcytic)", "Ferritin (low, iron deficiency common in children with pica)", "CMP, BUN, creatinine (renal function)", "Abdominal X-ray (radiopaque lead objects in GI tract)", "Long bone X-ray (lead lines (dense metaphyseal bands) in chronic exposure, not acute)", "Erythrocyte protoporphyrin (elevated, chronic exposure)"],
        treatment: "Remove source (identify and eliminate lead exposure). Gastrointestinal decontamination: whole bowel irrigation (PEG 3350, 1-2L/h) if radiopaque objects on X-ray. Chelation therapy: succimer (DMSA) 10mg/kg PO q8h x5 days, then q12h x14 days (for BLL 45-69). Edetate calcium disodium (CaNa2EDTA) 1000mg/m²/day IV or IM x5 days (for BLL >70, or encephalopathy, or severe symptoms). Dimercaprol (BAL) 75mg/m² IM q4h x5 days (for encephalopathy, in combination with EDTA). Monitor BLL during and after chelation (rebound). Treat seizures: benzodiazepines. Treat encephalopathy: mannitol 0.5-1g/kg IV if increased ICP. IV fluids. Monitor renal function (nephrotoxicity of chelators).",
        complication: ["Lead encephalopathy (10-20% of BLL >100, seizures, coma, cerebral edema, death)", "Seizures (10-20%)", "Coma (5-10%)", "Cerebral edema (5-10%)", "Chronic kidney disease (10-20%)", "Hypertension (20-30%)", "Peripheral neuropathy (wrist drop, foot drop, 10-20%)", "Developmental delay (children, irreversible, 50-80% of BLL >70)", "Death (1-5% of acute severe poisoning)"],
        prevention: "Remove lead-based paint (homes built before 1978), wet cleaning (reduce dust), hand hygiene, healthy diet (calcium, iron, vitamin C reduce absorption), avoid traditional remedies (azarcon, greta, pay-loo-ah), occupational safety (battery plants, smelters, construction), public education, screening for high-risk children (Medicaid, high-risk areas)",
