        ix: ["Chest X-ray (mass, nodule, atelectasis, pleural effusion, cavitation, Pancoast tumor (apical mass with rib destruction))", "CT chest (size, location, lymphadenopathy (mediastinal, hilar), invasion of chest wall, mediastinum, great vessels, pericardium, metastases to liver, adrenals, bone)", "PET-CT (metabolic activity (SUV max), metastases, staging, helps differentiate benign vs malignant, but false positive in infection, inflammation)", "Sputum cytology (if central tumor, 50-70% sensitive, non-invasive)", "Bronchoscopy with biopsy (for central tumors, endobronchial lesions, transbronchial needle aspiration (TBNA) for mediastinal lymph nodes)", "EBUS (endobronchial ultrasound, for mediastinal lymph node staging, biopsy)", "CT-guided transthoracic needle biopsy (for peripheral tumors, 90-95% sensitivity, 5-10% pneumothorax risk)", "Surgical biopsy (VATS or thoracotomy, if other methods non-diagnostic)", "Molecular testing (EGFR, ALK, ROS1, KRAS, BRAF, MET, RET, NTRK, PD-L1, on biopsy tissue, for targeted therapy and immunotherapy)", "CBC, CMP, LDH, calcium (paraneoplastic)", "CT head or MRI brain (rule out brain metastases, for staging)", "Bone scan or PET-CT (bone metastases)"],
        treatment: "Stage I-II (early, no lymph node metastases): surgical resection (lobectomy, segmentectomy, wedge resection) + mediastinal lymph node dissection. Adjuvant chemotherapy (cisplatin + vinorelbine, or carboplatin + paclitaxel) if high-risk (stage II, lymphovascular invasion, large tumor >4cm). Stage III (locally advanced, N2 lymph nodes): chemoradiation (cisplatin + etoposide, or carboplatin + paclitaxel, with concurrent radiation 60-66 Gy). Durvalumab (immunotherapy) after chemoradiation if no progression. Stage IV (metastatic): molecular testing for targeted therapy (EGFR: osimertinib, erlotinib, gefitinib; ALK: alectinib, lorlatinib, crizotinib; ROS1: crizotinib, entrectinib; BRAF V600E: dabrafenib + trametinib). Immunotherapy (pembrolizumab, nivolumab, atezolizumab) if PD-L1 ≥1-50% (first-line, alone or with chemotherapy). Chemotherapy (carboplatin + pemetrexed (non-squamous), or carboplatin + gemcitabine (squamous), or cisplatin + pemetrexed (non-squamous)). Palliative radiation for brain metastases, bone pain, SVC syndrome, hemoptysis.",
        complication: ["Metastases: brain (30-50%, headache, seizures, focal deficits), bone (20-40%, pain, fractures, cord compression), liver (20-30%, hepatomegaly, jaundice, ascites), adrenal (10-20%, usually asymptomatic), lung (contralateral, multiple nodules)", "Superior vena cava syndrome (5-10%, from mediastinal lymphadenopathy or tumor invasion, treat with steroids, radiation, stenting)", "Malignant pleural effusion (10-20%, dyspnea, treat with thoracentesis, pleurodesis, indwelling catheter)", "Hemoptysis (10-20%, massive 1-2%, treat with bronchial artery embolization, radiation, surgery)", "Post-obstructive pneumonia (10-20%, from bronchial obstruction, treat with antibiotics, bronchoscopy with debulking)", "Paraneoplastic syndromes (10-20%): hypercalcemia (squamous, treat with IV fluids, bisphosphonates, calcitonin), SIADH (small cell, treat with fluid restriction, demeclocycline, vaptans), Cushing (ACTH, small cell, treat with ketoconazole, metyrapone), Lambert-Eaton (small cell, treat with 3,4-diaminopyridine, IVIG)", "Death (5-year survival: stage IA 80-90%, IB 70-80%, IIA 50-60%, IIB 40-50%, IIIA 30-40%, IIIB 10-20%, IV <5%)"],
        prevention: "Smoking cessation (most important, reduces risk by 50% after 10 years), low-dose CT screening (annual, for adults 50-80 years with 20 pack-year smoking history, current or quit within 15 years, reduces lung cancer mortality by 20%), avoid secondhand smoke, asbestos, radon, occupational carcinogens (arsenic, chromium, nickel, cadmium, beryllium), diet high in fruits and vegetables (may reduce risk), chemoprevention (vitamin A, beta-carotene, vitamin E, selenium, no benefit, may increase risk in smokers)",
        epidemiology: "Most common cancer (2.2 million cases, 1.8 million deaths annually, 13% of all cancers, 20% of cancer deaths), 220,000 US cases, 150,000 US deaths annually, 85% non-small cell (adenocarcinoma 40%, squamous 30%, large cell 10-15%), 15% small cell, 80-90% in smokers, median age 70 years, 5-year survival 20% overall (early stage 60-90%, advanced <5%)"
