        ix: ["Clinical diagnosis (mechanical back pain, no red flags, no neurologic deficits)", "X-ray (if red flags, trauma, age >50, or persistent >4-6 weeks: degenerative changes, fractures, spondylolisthesis, tumor, infection)", "MRI (if red flags, or neurologic deficits, or persistent >6 weeks despite conservative treatment: disc herniation, stenosis, tumor, infection, fracture)", "CBC, ESR, CRP (if suspected infection, cancer, or inflammatory arthritis)", "Calcium, phosphorus, alkaline phosphatase (if suspected metabolic bone disease)"],
        treatment: "Acute (<4 weeks): activity modification (avoid aggravating activities, but stay active, bed rest not recommended >48h), ice or heat (15-20min q2-4h), acetaminophen 1g q6-8h (max 4g/day), NSAIDs (ibuprofen 400-800mg TID, naproxen 250-500mg BID) for 7-10 days (if no contraindications), muscle relaxants (cyclobenzaprine 5-10mg TID, or methocarbamol 500-750mg q6h, or baclofen 10mg TID) for 5-7 days (if severe muscle spasm). Subacute (4-12 weeks): physical therapy (core strengthening, back exercises, stretching, aerobic conditioning), manual therapy (spinal manipulation by chiropractor or PT), massage, acupuncture, yoga, cognitive behavioral therapy. Chronic (>12 weeks): same as subacute + multidisciplinary rehabilitation (pain psychology, vocational rehab, functional restoration), duloxetine 30-60mg daily (for chronic low back pain with or without depression), tramadol 50-100mg q6h (short-term, if NSAIDs contraindicated or ineffective). Avoid opioids (chronic use ineffective, risk of addiction, overdose, death). Surgery: discectomy, laminectomy, fusion (if cauda equina, progressive neurologic deficit, or disabling radiculopathy >6 weeks despite conservative treatment, or spinal instability).",
