        ix: ["Standing lateral X-ray (full spine, Cobb angle (between superior endplate of T4 to inferior endplate of T12, normal 20-40°, Scheuermann >45°), anterior wedging (≥5° in ≥3 adjacent vertebrae), Schmorl nodes, irregular endplates)", "Supine hyperextension lateral X-ray (over bolster, flexibility, surgical planning)", "MRI (if atypical (onset <10 or >20 years, pain >7/10, night pain, neurologic findings, rapid progression, or before surgery), to rule out tumor, infection, syrinx, Chiari, cord compression)", "Pulmonary function tests (if thoracic kyphosis >70°, FVC, FEV1, TLC, restrictive pattern)"],
        treatment: "Mild (Cobb 45-55°): observation (X-ray q6-12 months), physical therapy (extension exercises, hamstring stretching, core strengthening). Moderate (Cobb 55-70°, skeletally immature): bracing (Milwaukee brace, 18-23 hours/day, until skeletal maturity (Risser 4-5)), improves pain, stops progression, may reduce curve by 10-20°. Severe (Cobb >70°, or pain, or cosmetic concerns, or pulmonary restriction): posterior spinal fusion with instrumentation (pedicle screws, rods) and osteotomies (Smith-Petersen, Ponte, pedicle subtraction) for rigid curves. Average correction 50-70%. Anterior release and fusion for rigid curves (>90°, or kyphosis >100°).",
